This article discusses the benefits of apprenticeship programs in the United States. It highlights the fact that there are currently 6 million job openings in the country, but a skills gap exists, making it difficult for companies to find qualified employees. The skills gap is particularly prevalent in sectors such as financial services, healthcare, and information technology. The article emphasizes that apprenticeship programs can help bridge this gap by providing individuals with demand-based skills and good, stable jobs. Graduates of apprenticeship programs typically earn a starting wage of over $60,000 per year, higher than the average starting salary of college graduates. However, apprenticeships currently make up only 0.3 percent of the American workforce, with large-scale programs mostly limited to the construction sector. The article concludes by stating that President Trump recognizes the value of apprenticeships and intends to expand job opportunities through such programs.